SUMMARY:Should India Ban Social Media for Children?
DESCRIPTION:The question has moved from op-ed to assembly floor. \nKarnataka and Andhra Pradesh have announced bans on social media for children under sixteen. Goa is weighing it\, Australia has already implemented it. India’s Economic Survey has urged the Union Government to follow suit. \nAdvocates say the evidence is damning: rising anxiety\, fractured attention\, and childhoods quietly colonised by algorithmic design. Opponents say the cure is worse than the disease: the bans drive harm underground\, widen inequality\, and mistake control for care. \nThis evening examines the issue through the discipline of Purva Paksha. Each speaker first presents the other’s argument\, fully and fairly\, before offering their own. The aim is not to win\, but rather to understand what protecting a child actually demands of us. \nIn collaboration with: \n \n
URL:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/event/should-india-ban-social-media-for-children/
LOCATION:Bangalore International Centre\, 7\, 4th Main Road\, Domlur II Stage\, Bangalore\, Karnataka\, 560071\, India
CATEGORIES:Governance,Media,Policy & Regulation,Society,Technology
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://bangaloreinternationalcentre.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Thumbnail-26.jpg
END:VEVENT
